(1732, 'Review special teams\' performances and any significant plays that could influence the game.', 'Special Teams Analysis Agent', 'Medium', '2024-12-08 18:41:36', 40, 1, 'To assess the potential impact of special teams performances on the game between the Chicago Bears and the San Francisco 49ers on December 8, 2024, here are some factual points gathered from credible sources:\n\n## Special Teams Performance Statistics\n\n- **Field Goals and Scoring**: As of the 2024 season, the 49ers have made 28 field goals out of 34 attempts (82.4% success rate), while the Bears have made 16 out of 20 attempts (80% success rate)[2].\n\n## Special Teams Metrics\n\n- **Kickoffs and Kickoff Returns**: There is no detailed breakdown of kickoff and kickoff return statistics in the provided sources, but special teams scoring and field goal percentages can indicate overall special teams efficiency.\n- **Punting and Punt Returns**: The sources do not provide specific punting and punt return statistics for the 2024 season, but general special teams performance can be inferred from scoring and field goal data.\n\n## Recent Team Performance\n\n- **Bears\' Special Teams**: While the Bears have a respectable field goal success rate, their overall special teams performance has not been a significant standout in the season so far. However, their defense, which includes aspects influenced by special teams, has been ranked relatively well, allowing 20.0 points per game on average[1].\n- **49ers\' Special Teams**: The 49ers have a higher success rate in field goals, which could be an advantage in close games. However, their recent performances have been impacted by various factors, including injuries and defensive struggles, particularly without key players like Nick Bosa[5].\n\n## Key Players and Injuries\n\n- **Injuries and Player Availability**: There is no specific information on special teams players being injured or unavailable, but general team injuries could affect special teams units